@node WhatIsIt "What is IQuotation?"
@{b}What is it?@{ub}

IQuotation is a simple program which selects a random quotation
from a pre-formatted file of quotations.
@endnode


@node Requirements "What you need to run IQuotation"
@{b}What are the program requirements?@{ub}

An Amiga (you can pick your processor from the 4 provided),
running OS 2.x or higher.

@{b}@{i}WARNING:@{ub}@{ui} this program has only been tested by
me on my Amiga 500 running with a GVP A530 under OS 3.1.
But the program doesn't use anything peculiar to OS 3.x.
You must understand that you cannot hold me liable for any
damage to your computer.  The program is free, and you get
what you pay for.
@endnode

@node HowIUse "How to use IQuotation"
@{b}How do I use it?@{ub}

Make sure a properly-formatted file named Quotes.txt is in your
S: directory, and just double-click on the icon.

@{b}What if I want to use it from a shell?@{ub}

Fine, just type "IQuotation" from a shell prompt.
@endnode

@node Options "IQuotation Options (Option, really)"
@{b}Don't I have any options?@{ub}

Sure: if you want to use a different filename, change the
@{b}FILENAME@{ub} tooltype to that file.  If you prefer the shell
interface, type "IQuotation FILENAME=<filename>".  It
really couldn't be simpler.
@endnode

@node HowIMake "Making your own quotation files"
@{b}How do I make my own quotation files?@{ub}

Very easily.  The first line of the files should have the
number of quotes in the file. The next line should be a tilde
(~).  Then you put your quote in, ending it with a tilde (~).
Continue in this quote-tilde-quote-tilde fashion until you're
done!

For an example, see the supplied Quotes.txt.

I should probably mention that I shamelessly stole this format
from the program "Quotation" whose author I have forgotten.
(Nice program, though.  I use it.)
@endnode

